|Republican]]\n|religion     =[[Disciples of Christ]] \n|spouse       =Patty Williams\n|children     =Two daughters\n|website      =[http://williams.house.gov/ Representative Roger Williams]\n|footnotes    =  \n}}\n\n'''John Roger Williams''' (born September 13, 1949) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Texas's 25th congressional district]] since 2013. Previously, he served under [[Governor of Texas|Governor]] [[Rick Perry]] as [[Secretary of State of Texas]] from November 2004 to July 1, 2007. \n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nWilliams was reared in [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]]. He was a star [[baseball]] player for [[Texas Christian University]] (TCU) from 1968 to 1971 and attempted to play professionally with the [[Atlanta Braves]] farm team. He returned to Texas to coach TCU's  baseball team before he embarked on a career in [[business]] and public affairs. Williams joined his father in a family [[automobile]] dealership founded in 1939.\n\n==Early political activism (1994-2004)==\nHe served as Regional Finance Chairman for [[George W. Bush as Governor of Texas|Governor George W. Bush]] in his 1994 and 1998 elections. He became North Texas Chairman for the [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2000|Bush/Cheney 2000 campaign]], North Texas Finance Chairman in 2004, and National Grassroots Fundraising Chairman for the [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2004|2004 campaign]]. Williams was appointed by President [[George W. Bush]] in 2001 to be Chairman of the Republican National Finance Committee\u2019s Eagles Program. \n\nHe has also served as State Finance Chair for [[John Cornyn]]'s [[United States Senate election in Texas, 2002|U.S. Senate campaign]] and as the National Director of the \"Patriots\" program for Cornyn.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joel |url=http://www.rogerforcongress.com/meet-roger |title=Roger Williams for Congress &#124; Meet Roger |publisher=Rogerforcongress.com |date=2005-02-08 |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Perry administration (2002-2007)==\nWilliams was appointed by Governor Perry to the Texas Motor Vehicle Board. He was nominated by [[Lieutenant Governor]] [[Bill Ratliff]] to the Special Committee on State Employee Compensation and Benefits.\n\nPerry appointed Williams to be his fourth [[Secretary of State of Texas]]. As secretary of state, Williams was the Chief Elections Officer for Texas, assisted county election officials and ensured the uniform application and interpretation of election laws through the state. He oversaw the state\u2019s efforts to comply with the federal [[Help America Vote Act]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nWilliams worked to promote economic development, investment, and job creation in Texas.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}} He was also Perry's chief liaison to [[Mexico]] and the Border Region of Texas. In this capacity, he worked with Mexican federal, state, and local officials on common issues.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nAs the overseer and director of Texas elections, Williams's office was in the spotlight during the [[Texas gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 Texas governor's race]]. Independent candidate [[Kinky Friedman|Richard Friedman]] (commonly known as \"Kinky\") successfully lobbied to have the name \"Kinky\" placed on the election ballot. Another Independent candidate, [[Carole K. Strayhorn]], sought to have the name \"Grandma\" placed on the ballot next to her name. (Strayhorn's campaign slogan was \"one tough grandma\".) Strayhorn's request was denied. Friedman and Strayhorn finished third and fourth, respectively, in the election, behind Democrat [[Chris Bell (politician)|Chris Bell]] and the winner, incumbent Republican Perry.\n\nWilliams announced on June 11, 2007, that he would leave the appointed position to \"pursue other opportunities\".\n\n==State Victory chairman (2007-2008)==\nOn July 16, 2007, Williams was named chairman of the Texas [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Victory 2008 Coordinated Campaign, which assists candidates up and down the [[general election]] ballot.<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/state_news/story/171326.html ]{{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>  Republicans again won all statewide office in 2008 and gained a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives]] but lost four seats in the [[Texas House of Representatives]] and county offices in populous [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]].\n\nLate in 2008, Williams formed an exploratory committee to consider a run for the [[United States Senate]] seat held by fellow Republican [[Kay Bailey Hutchison]] of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]], who had formed her own committee to consider a 2010 race for governor of Texas. Williams considered a run for Senate in 2012 but decided to run for Congress instead.<ref name=\"williamsswitches\">{{cite web |url= http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2011/06/roger-williams-switches-from-s.html|title= Roger Williams switches from Senate to House race |author= Wayne Slater|date= 28 June 2011|work= Trailblazers Blog|publisher= Dallas Morning News|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{Seealso|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2012#District 25}}\nIn June 2011, Williams announced that he was dropping his Senate bid and would instead run for [[Texas' 25th congressional district]]<ref name=\"williamsswitches\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Alex |url=http://www.rogerforcongress.com |title=Roger Williams for Congress |publisher=Rogerforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>  Williams ranked first with 25% of the vote, failing to meet the threshold and qualifying for the run-off election. Wes Riddle ranked second with 15% of the vote, qualifying for the run-off election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=739104 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref> In the July 31 election, Williams defeated Riddle 58%-42%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=767639 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref> In the November general election, Williams defeated Democratic nominee Elaine Henderson 58%-37%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=759994 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>\n\n===2014 election===\n\nIn the November 4, 2014 general election, Williams will face the Democrat Marco Montoya, who in his primary on March 4 polled 11,294 votes (75 percent) of the ballots cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=3852&id=407|title=Democratic primary election returns|publisher=team1.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=March 6, 2014}}</ref> Williams is also planning to challenge [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] Chairman [[Greg Walden]] in his bid for a second term as chairman after the 2014 elections. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Center|first1=Shira|title=Roger Williams Makes Play for NRCC Chairman|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/nrcc-chairman-roger-williams-greg-walden/?dcz=emailalert|website=www.rollcall.com|publisher=Roll Call|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams and his wife, Patty, live in [[Weatherford, Texas|Weatherford]], the seat of [[Parker County, Texas|Parker County]] west of Fort Worth, and have two daughters who attended TCU. He owns an [[automobile]] dealership in Weatherford. He attends the University Christian Church in Fort Worth.\n\nWilliams is a trustee of TCU and the [[George Bush School of Government and Public Service]] at [[Texas A&M University]] in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]]. \n\n{{Portal|Illinois|Texas|Baseball|Politics}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://williams.house.gov/ Congressman Roger Williams] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.rogerforcongress.com/ Roger Williams for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Roger_Williams_%5BR-25%5D|Roger Williams}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = W000816 | ballot = Roger_Williams | nndb = 839/000118485 | votesmart = 50112 | govtrack = 412578 | opencong = 412578 | rollcall = 44864 | politifact = roger-williams | fec = H2TX33040 | opensecrets = N00030602 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = | ontheissues = TX/Roger_Williams.htm | congress = roger-williams/2165 | worldcat = | c-span = rogerwilliams03 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = 46eb6828-4bbd-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{baseballstats|brm=willia005rog|cube=Roger-Williams-1}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Secretary of State of Texas]]<br />John Roger Williams\n| before=[[Geoff Connor]]\n| after=[[Phil Wilson (Texas politician)|Samuel Philip \"Phil\" Wilson]]\n| years=2004\u20132007\n}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=Texas|\n  district=25 |\n  before=[[Lloyd Doggett]] |\n  start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brad Wenstrup]]<br><small>R-[[Ohio]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Repres